<div id="review_2446075321" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2446075321" />
    <a title="Gary Letham" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21648117-gary-letham"><img alt="Gary Letham" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1372193472p2/21648117.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2446075321?book_show_action=true">Jul 05, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gary Letham" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gary Letham" href="/user/show/21648117-gary-letham">Gary Letham</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2446075321" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13865716978700012707">The story of the Blood family, Vermont farmers from 1944 onwards. It starts with a tragedy, Loyal Blood, eldest son of Mink &amp; Jewell Blood kills his girlfriend Billie and buries her body in a hollow under a large walling stone. In order to hide this crime he immediately tell his family that he and Billie are heading west to make a new life for themselves. Mink, Loyal&apos;s father does not take this well, he is partially crippled, and the younger son Dub only has one arm. It is evident that without L</span>
  <span id="freeText13865716978700012707" style="display:none">The story of the Blood family, Vermont farmers from 1944 onwards. It starts with a tragedy, Loyal Blood, eldest son of Mink &amp; Jewell Blood kills his girlfriend Billie and buries her body in a hollow under a large walling stone. In order to hide this crime he immediately tell his family that he and Billie are heading west to make a new life for themselves. Mink, Loyal's father does not take this well, he is partially crippled, and the younger son Dub only has one arm. It is evident that without Loyal's continued help, Mink &amp; Dub will struggle to run the farm. Loyal appears to have been the favoured son, and Mink has implemented improvements suggested by Loyal such as increasing their dairy herd with Holsteins and their greater milk yield, rather than the Jerseys they have traditionally farmed with. Minks temper explodes and he smashes up the house, and shoots the Holsteins. We are made aware from this that Loyal has inherited his fathers temper and although not revealed, may be the root of Billies death. <br />The book from this point id the story of the farms decline and the enforced changes resulting from Minks rash attempt to escape financial ruin.<br />Jewel realises her life and world are bigger than the farm and Minks repressive violent behaviour. She learns to drive and gets a job.<br />Mernelle, the daughter escapes the farm by replying to an advert from Ray, looking for a wife. Second son and black sheep Dub finds his way to Florida by way of prison, a mail scam into a lucrative real estate career.<br />The main story however is that of Loyal, and his self imposed exile living hand to mouth across America, labouring, working in mines, collector of dinosaur bones and finally back to his very first talent of trapping. As with Annies books the prose is rich and superb, and describes in depth the flora and fauna of the surrounding so much so it becomes part of the narrative. This reminded me greatly of Edward Abbey's writings and his descriptions of the American south West. <br />A novel of guilt, discovery and loss that should not be missed</span>
  <a data-text-id="13865716978700012707" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


