    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2228684408" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2228684408" />
    <a title="Hannah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9784757-hannah"><img alt="Hannah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471992670p2/9784757.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2228684408?book_show_action=true">Dec 27, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hannah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hannah" href="/user/show/9784757-hannah">Hannah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2228684408" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9194166921574563404">The book starts with Loyal Blood killing his fiancee Billy and hiding her in a stone wall on his family farm. He then flees and starts a trek across the nation. He communicates with his family via postcards. While the story focuses on him and his wanderings, there are occasional snapshots of the family that he left behind. His angry father Mink, his complacent mother Jewell, his one-armed brother Dub, and his dreamy sister Mernelle.<br/><br/>The story has been described as the disintegration of a family. </span>
  <span id="freeText9194166921574563404" style="display:none">The book starts with Loyal Blood killing his fiancee Billy and hiding her in a stone wall on his family farm. He then flees and starts a trek across the nation. He communicates with his family via postcards. While the story focuses on him and his wanderings, there are occasional snapshots of the family that he left behind. His angry father Mink, his complacent mother Jewell, his one-armed brother Dub, and his dreamy sister Mernelle.<br /><br />The story has been described as the disintegration of a family. I can agree with that. The family, very consciously, had relied on Loyal to continue the family farm and when he left, there was no backup plan. I loved the snapshots more then the story about Loyal. I related better to the tales of Jewell having to learn how to drive and Mernelle reading Lonely Hearts ads looking for love.<br /><br />Loyal lives a life of quiet desperation. He mines, he looks for uranium, he traps animals. He is a farmer who cannot farm. He feels neither content or discontent. Loyal is attempting to survive. While he is not a character that I found particularly likeable, neither did I dislike him. His story was enthralling without actually bringing you closer to the main character.<br /><br />I thought it was good, but I preferred "The Shipping News". I thought those characters were a little stronger then these.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9194166921574563404" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


